  "citation": "Hull, L., Mandy, W., Lai, M.-C., Baron-Cohen, S., Allison, C., Smith, P., & Petrides, K. V. (2019). Development and Validation of the Self-Report Camouflaging Autistic Traits Questionnaire (CAT-Q). Journal of Autism and Developmental Disorders, 49(3), 819-833.",
  "publicDomain": false,
  "licensingNote": "Copyrighted to Hull et al. Personal/dev testing only \u2014 MUST NOT ship to TestFlight or production until licensing signed with Laura Hull.",
  "validityNotes": "CAT-Q measures camouflaging effort across three subscales: Compensation (9 items, learning/practicing social strategies), Masking (8 items, hiding autistic traits / projecting a non-autistic persona), Assimilation (8 items, effort to fit in or avoid interaction). No formal clinical cutoff. Hull et al. 2019 reference ranges: autistic sample mean ~124 (SD ~13), non-autistic sample mean ~91 (SD ~20), substantial overlap. Especially useful for late-identified adults whose camouflaging causes AQ-10 to underestimate the underlying pattern.",
